{
  "doc_id": "8232",
  "text": "Acute exacerbations are well recognized in IPF [CITATION_1] , but have also been described in hypersensitivity pneumonitis [CITATION_2] . They are characterized by fast progressive dyspnoea and the occurrence of new bilateral ground-glass opacities on high-resolution computed tomography (HRCT); exclusion of heart failure, infection or pulmonary embolism is mandatory [CITATION_3] . Risk factors are low total lung capacity of diffusing capacity for carbon monoxide, a usual interstitial pneumonia (UIP)-like pattern on histology and increased neutrophils and decreased lymphocytes in BAL fluid [CITATION_4] .",
